---
import { IsolatedSessions, SessionDissolve } from '@metaharness/animations';
import VizSurface from '../../VizSurface.astro';
---

<section
  id="memory"
  class="border-y border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-100/60 px-6 py-20 md:py-28 dark:border-neutral-900 dark:bg-neutral-900/40"
>
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-6xl">
    <div class="max-w-3xl">
      <h2
        class="text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-neutral-900 sm:text-4xl dark:text-neutral-50"
      >
        The knowledge dissolves with the session
      </h2>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-12 grid min-w-0 items-center gap-12 lg:grid-cols-2">
      <div
        class="space-y-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-700 dark:text-neutral-300"
      >
        <p>
          There is a second shift hiding inside the first. Work used to be one
          person per problem; now it is <mark>you plus a handful of agents</mark
          >. You operate like an architect: you care that the data flows through
          the system the right way, you do not sit at the keyboard of every
          change. The agent holds those details, the way a coworker used to.
        </p>
        <p>
          Every company knows how that story ends. The coworker who knows why
          the payment retry logic looks the way it does changes jobs, and the
          knowledge leaves with them. <strong
            class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 dark:text-neutral-50"
            >With agents, that does not happen once a year. It happens every
            time a session ends.</strong
          >
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="min-w-0">
        <VizSurface>
          <SessionDissolve client:visible className="mx-auto" />
        </VizSurface>
      </div>
    </div>

    <figure
      class="mx-auto mt-14 max-w-4xl border-y border-neutral-300 py-10 text-center dark:border-neutral-800"
    >
      <p
        class="text-2xl font-medium leading-snug text-neutral-900 sm:text-3xl dark:text-neutral-100"
      >
        Agents are developers who <span class="text-accent"
          >leave after every single task</span
        >.
      </p>
    </figure>

    <div id="multiplayer" class="mt-20">
      <div class="max-w-3xl">
        <h2
          class="text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-neutral-900 sm:text-4xl dark:text-neutral-50"
        >
          And real work is multiplayer
        </h2>
      </div>

      <div class="mt-12 grid min-w-0 items-center gap-12 lg:grid-cols-2">
        <div class="lg:order-last">
          <div
            class="space-y-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-700 dark:text-neutral-300"
          >
            <p>
              Real work within an organization is much more complex than one
              person's. Your teammates run their own sessions against the same
              systems, all day, every day. Each session solves problems, rules
              out approaches, encodes decisions.
            </p>
            <p>
              Real work builds on the work that came before it. Someone on your
              team has almost certainly worked through the exact area you are
              about to touch, but your agent has no way of knowing what your
              coworker's agent did. While the organization runs hundreds of
              sessions, all of them stay <mark
                >local to the developer's machine, invisible to everyone else</mark
              >.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="min-w-0">
          <VizSurface>
            <IsolatedSessions client:visible className="mx-auto" />
          </VizSurface>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
